//   String Notes
String : 
-->import Java.lang.String;

1. A String in Java is a sequence of characters Arrys.
2. Strings are objects of the String class, which belongs to the java.lang package.
3. We can create a string directly by using double Single quotation in java ''.
4. Immutable â€” methods return new String objects; original string does not change.

Example : String s1 = 'Hello';
          String s = 'Hello'; refereance  

5. String is a final class, so we cannot extend it.

#. There are two ways to create strings in Java:

[1.] Using String Literals ==>

      String s1 = 'Hello, World!';

[2.] new String(...) constructors(Keyword) ==>  6 types   see in Strings/Strings.java file

[3.] StringBuffer ==> A mutable (changeable) sequence of characters. Thread-safe (synchronized[]).

// String Extraction in Java ======>>

[1.] char ch = str.charAt(2): Used to extract one character from a specific index.
[2.] s.toCharArray():  The string "Hello" was converted to a character array: ['H','e','l','l','o'].
      Example :
            String s = "Hello";
            char[] arr = s.toCharArray();

[3.] s.getChars(int srcBegin, int srcEnd, char[] dest, int destBegin)  Show getChars.java file.
[4.] s.substring(int beginIndex): Returns a new string that is a substring of this string.
      Example :
            String s = "Hello, World!";
            String sub = s.substring(7); // "World!"

[5.] s.substring(int beginIndex, int endIndex): Returns a new string that is a substring of this string.
      Example :
            String s = "Hello, World!";
            String sub = s.substring(0, 5); // "Hello"

[6.] s.split(String regex): Splits this string around matches of the given regular expression.
      Example :
            String s = "apple,banana,cherry";
            String[] fruits = s.split(","); // ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
[7.] s.length(): Returns the length of this string.
      Example :
            String s = "Hello";
            int len = s.length(); // 5

[8.] s.lowercase() and uppercase(): Converts all characters in the string to lower case or upper case.
      Example :
            String s = "Hello";
            String lower = s.toLowerCase(); // "hello"
            String upper = s.toUpperCase(); // "HELLO"
[8.] s.getbytes(): Encodes this String into a sequence of bytes using the platform's default charset, storing the result into a new byte array.
      Example :
            String s = "Hello";
            byte[] byteArray = s.getBytes(); // [72, 101, 108, 108, 111] (ASCII values)            


     
